
1. Why is GitHub signup important for developers?

GitHub accounts enable version control, collaboration, and portfolio building. Developers use it to track code changes, work in teams via pull requests, and showcase projects to employers.​​

Key advantages:

    Host unlimited public/private repositories

    Contribute to open source (builds credibility)

    Access GitHub Actions for CI/CD automation

    Network with 100M+ developers globally



2. What details are required to create a GitHub account?

Creating a GitHub account needs just three essentials:

| Field    | Requirement       | Tips                                  |
| -------- | ----------------- | ------------------------------------- |
| Email    | Valid address     | Used for notifications + verification |
| Password | Strong (8+ chars) | Enable 2FA immediately after          |
| Username | Unique handle     | Professional (no "coolguy123")        |

Process: Email → Password → Username → CAPTCHA → Email verification (2 minutes total).



3. What happens after successful GitHub signup?

	After verification, users land on personal dashboard with:

    "New repository" button (create first project)

    Explore tab (trending repos, topics)

    Profile README setup prompt

    GitHub Copilot trial (AI code assistant)

Immediate actions:

1. Create first repo: "my-portfolio"
2. Add README.md with skills/projects  
3. Follow 5 relevant developers/companies
4. Star 10 useful repositories



4. Can GitHub be used without signing up?

Public access works (view/download repos), but core features locked:

| With Account ✅     | Without Account ❌ |
| ------------------ | ----------------- |
| Create/fork repos  | View only         |
| Pull requests      | Cannot contribute |
| Issues/discussions | Read-only         |
| GitHub Actions     | Cannot run CI/CD  |
| Private repos      | No access         |

Bottom line: Browsing free, building requires signup.



5. Why is GitHub profile useful for jobs?

GitHub = Digital resume checked by 95% of hiring managers:


No GitHub → "Shows no real projects"
Active GitHub → "Built 5 apps, 200+ commits, open source contributions"

Recruiter checklist:

    10+ commits weekly activity

    3+ pinned repositories (best projects)

    README with screenshots + demo links

    Contributions graph (consistent work)

Real impact: Internship offers require GitHub link in 80% of applications.
